replies.bodyText:
It's not too bad, I think it should be fine as is then. Just don't want there to be too many variations. Some of the convenience ends up being more confusing. might not be recognizable that copy means producing a new duplicate of the original. I don't think new BlockRegion(a) is any more convenient then a.copy().
BlockRegion b = new BlockRegion(0,0,0,0,0,0);
BlockRegion temp =  b.copy();

vs

BlockRegion b = new BlockRegion(0,0,0,0,0,0);
BlockRegion temp =  new BlockRegion(b); 

the copy method hides the instantiation so its not apparent what is exactly happening at a glance. feels like something that is convenient at the cost of readability.
I guess you've also hidden all the constructor methods so you basically need a copy method. The whole process of shifting everything to a utility class and hiding an instantiation in a method just seems strange to me. The whole things feels a bit like taking an additional detour.

I actually did re-expose the constructors for min/max and single block position, as well as the copy-constructor taking another region. What's still left on the utility class are constructors for fromMinAndSize and fromCenterAndExtents.
I can remove the copy method, but then I'd also go for removing the utility class, as
fromMinAndSize(min, size) == new BlockRegion(min).setSize(size);

fromCenterAndExtents(center, extents) == new BlockRegion(center).expand(extents);
It would be nice to make BlockRegion implements Iterable, but then we'd need to throw out on of the iterables, too (preferably keep in the in-place variant, as you can implement the other on caller side).

